⚠️ EXPLICIT RETURN TYPES REQUIRED:
All functions and methods MUST have explicit return types.

This project enforces explicit typing for better type safety and IDE support.

❌ NEVER omit return types:
```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function getUser(id: string) {
  return users.find(u => u.id === id);
}

// ❌ BAD
const processData = (data) => {
  return data.map(item => item.value);
};
```

✅ ALWAYS specify return types:
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
function getUser(id: string): User | undefined {
  return users.find((u: User): boolean => u.getId() === id);
}

// ✅ GOOD
const processData = (data: DataItem[]): number[] => {
  return data.map((item: DataItem): number => item.getValue());
};

// ✅ GOOD: Async functions
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  const response: Response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  const data: unknown = await response.json();
  return User.fromJSON(data);
}

// ✅ GOOD: Void for no return
public updateEmail(email: string): void {
  this._email = email;
}

// ✅ GOOD: Never for functions that never return
function throwError(message: string): never {
  throw new Error(message);
}
```

**Return type guidelines:**
  - Use 'void' for functions with no return value
  - Use 'Promise<Type>' for async functions
  - Use 'Type | undefined' for nullable returns
  - Use 'never' for functions that throw or infinite loop
  - Specify array types: 'Type[]' not just 'Array'

See: .claude/rules/strict-typing-class-patterns.md
